{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17570146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17570146"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:38:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:38:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22754"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22754"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.72,0.03,0.07,0.13,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15701"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111833"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15701"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22754"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93903"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"299"},{"type":"tags","id":"1022"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"4213"},{"type":"tags","id":"4452"},{"type":"tags","id":"4506"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45640"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45641"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45642"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45643"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111833"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman is admitted to the tertiary obstetric unit at 25 weeks gestation with preterm prelabour rupture of membranes (PPROM). She has been managed expectantly for the past 48 hours, during which time she has received a course of corticosteroids, nifedipine for tocolysis, and magnesium sulphate for fetal neuroprotection. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy multivitamins. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she now appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a tender uterus. Ultrasound shows a single live fetus in breech presentation with oligohydramnios. High vaginal swabs are taken. Blood tests reveal a white cell count of 18 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E (4-11) and C-reactive protein of 80 mg/L (\u003C5).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Caesarean section","External cephalic version","Continued expectant management","Induction of labour","Amnioinfusion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient, who has been managed expectantly for PPROM, has now developed signs of chorioamnionitis, indicated by maternal fever, tachycardia, uterine tenderness, elevated white cell count, and raised C-reactive protein. Given this complication, along with the extremely preterm gestation (25 weeks) and breech presentation, urgent delivery via \u003Cstrong\u003Ecaesarean section\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinued expectant management\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate due to the presence of chorioamnionitis. This serious complication necessitates immediate delivery regardless of gestational age due to the risk of severe maternal and fetal infection, even though the patient has already received steroids, tocolysis, and magnesium sulphate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal cephalic version\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in cases of PPROM due to the increased risk of cord prolapse and placental abruption. Moreover, it would be inappropriate to attempt this procedure in the presence of chorioamnionitis and at such an early gestational age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInduction of labour\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate for an extremely preterm breech presentation at 25 weeks. The risks of cord prolapse and head entrapment are significantly increased, particularly with oligohydramnios.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmnioinfusion\u003C/strong\u003E involves instilling fluid into the amniotic cavity and is sometimes used in cases of oligohydramnios. However, it is contraindicated in the presence of chorioamnionitis and would not address the urgent need for delivery in this infected patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegarding the type of caesarean section, a classical caesarean section (vertical uterine incision) is often preferred over a lower segment caesarean section for extremely preterm deliveries, especially in breech presentations. This approach provides better access to the fetus and reduces the risk of difficult extraction. However, it\u0027s important to note that classical caesarean sections are associated with increased maternal morbidity and impact future pregnancies, requiring caesarean delivery for all subsequent births due to the risk of uterine rupture. The specific surgical approach would be determined by the obstetrician based on individual circumstances.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Preterm prelabour rupture of membranes (PPROM) with chorioamnionitis requires urgent delivery regardless of gestational age.","Classical caesarean section is the preferred method for delivering extremely preterm breech presentations.","Oligohydramnios in PPROM increases the risk of cord prolapse and fetal compromise."],"references":["Kan A. Classical Cesarean Section. Surg J (N Y). 2020 Feb 6;6(Suppl 2):S98-S103. doi: 10.1055/s-0039-3402072. PMID: 32760792; PMCID: PMC7396476."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93903"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22754"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93903"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-20T10:57:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-20T11:00:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15701"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111833"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"he